    The crash is caused by dereferencing an invalidated std::vector<int>        
    iterator.                                                                   
                                                                                
    At line 10:                                                                 
                                                                                
                                                                                
     auto it = v.begin() + 2;                                                   
                                                                                
                                                                                
    it points to the third element of the vector, initially the value 3.        
                                                                                
    The vector starts as:                                                       
                                                                                
                                                                                
     std::vector<int> v = {1, 2, 3, 4};                                         
                                                                                
                                                                                
    So conceptually:                                                            
                                                                                
                                                                                
     v = [1, 2, 3, 4]                                                           
               ^                                                                
               it                                                               
                                                                                
                                                                                
    Then the program does:                                                      
                                                                                
                                                                                
     for (int i = 0; i < 1000; ++i) {                                           
         v.push_back(i);                                                        
     }                                                                          
                                                                                
                                                                                
    std::vector stores its elements in a contiguous heap allocation. When       
    push_back needs more capacity than the current allocation can hold, the     
    vector allocates a new larger buffer, moves/copies the existing elements    
    into it, and frees the old buffer.                                          
                                                                                
    Any iterator, pointer, or reference into the old buffer becomes invalid     
    after such a reallocation.                                                  
                                                                                
    In this program, it still points into the vectorâ€™s original storage. After  
    enough push_back calls â€” likely on the very first one, since the initial    
    vector may have capacity exactly 4 â€” v reallocates. The old buffer is       
    freed, but it is not updated.                                               
                                                                                
    Then line 14 does:                                                          
                                                                                
                                                                                
     std::printf("element via stale iter: %d\n", *it);                          
                                                                                
                                                                                
    That dereferences it, which points into deallocated memory.                 
    AddressSanitizer reports this as:                                           
                                                                                
                                                                                
     Use of deallocated memory                                                  
                                                                                
                                                                                
    So the defect is not in printf; it is that the program keeps and later      
    dereferences a std::vector iterator across operations that can invalidate   
    it.                                                                         
                                                                                
    A minimal local fix is to not preserve the iterator across the push_back    
    loop. Store an index instead and reacquire the element after the vector     
    has finished growing:                                                       
                                                                                
                                                                                
     #include <cstdio>                                                          
     #include <vector>                                                          
                                                                                
     int main()                                                                 
     {                                                                          
         std::vector<int> v = {1, 2, 3, 4};                                     
                                                                                
         std::size_t index = 2;                                                 
                                                                                
         for (int i = 0; i < 1000; ++i) {                                       
             v.push_back(i);                                                    
         }                                                                      
                                                                                
         std::printf("element via index: %d\n", v[index]);                      
         return 0;                                                              
     }                                                                          
                                                                                
                                                                                
    Alternatively, if the program only wants the original value that it         
    pointed to before the vector was modified, copy that value before mutating  
    the vector:                                                                 
                                                                                
                                                                                
     #include <cstdio>                                                          
     #include <vector>                                                          
                                                                                
     int main()                                                                 
     {                                                                          
         std::vector<int> v = {1, 2, 3, 4};                                     
                                                                                
         int element = v[2];                                                    
                                                                                
         for (int i = 0; i < 1000; ++i) {                                       
             v.push_back(i);                                                    
         }                                                                      
                                                                                
         std::printf("original element: %d\n", element);                        
         return 0;                                                              
     }                                                                          
                                                                                
                                                                                
    Another possible local fix is to reserve enough capacity before taking the  
    iterator:                                                                   
                                                                                
                                                                                
     #include <cstdio>                                                          
     #include <vector>                                                          
                                                                                
     int main()                                                                 
     {                                                                          
         std::vector<int> v = {1, 2, 3, 4};                                     
                                                                                
         v.reserve(v.size() + 1000);                                            
                                                                                
         auto it = v.begin() + 2;                                               
                                                                                
         for (int i = 0; i < 1000; ++i) {                                       
             v.push_back(i);                                                    
         }                                                                      
                                                                                
         std::printf("element via iter: %d\n", *it);                            
         return 0;                                                              
     }                                                                          
                                                                                
                                                                                
    That works because the later push_back calls will not need to reallocate.   
    However, this is a more fragile fix: if the number of insertions changes,   
    or if another operation that invalidates iterators is added, the bug can    
    return.                                                                     
                                                                                
    The more thorough root-cause fix is to avoid designing code that keeps      
    std::vector iterators, pointers, or references alive across vector          
    mutations that may reallocate. Prefer one of these patterns:                
                                                                                
                                                                                
     std::size_t index = 2;                                                     
     // mutate vector                                                           
     use(v[index]);                                                             
                                                                                
                                                                                
    or:                                                                         
                                                                                
                                                                                
     // mutate vector                                                           
     auto it = v.begin() + 2;                                                   
     use(*it);                                                                  
                                                                                
                                                                                
    or, if you need pointer/iterator stability, use a container with more       
    suitable invalidation behavior, such as std::deque or std::list, depending  
    on the exact access and mutation requirements.                              
                                                                                
    Recommendation                                                              
                                                                                
    Fix the bug by not using an iterator after push_back operations that may    
    reallocate the vector. The best minimal fix here is:                        
                                                                                
                                                                                
     #include <cstdio>                                                          
     #include <vector>                                                          
                                                                                
     int main()                                                                 
     {                                                                          
         std::vector<int> v = {1, 2, 3, 4};                                     
                                                                                
         std::size_t index = 2;                                                 
                                                                                
         for (int i = 0; i < 1000; ++i) {                                       
             v.push_back(i);                                                    
         }                                                                      
                                                                                
         std::printf("element via index: %d\n", v[index]);                      
         return 0;                                                              
     }                                                                          
                                                                                
                                                                                
    If the intended behavior is to print the original third element regardless  
    of later vector changes, use:                                               
                                                                                
                                                                                
     int element = v[2];                                                        
                                                                                
                                                                                
    before the loop and print element after the loop.                           
                                                                                
